      p It has taken me time to learn that politics is a life decision. That is, not only to exercise every 5 years our right to participate in the elections of rulers, but to participate daily in the decisions we make among ourselves for the good coexistence in society. How we interact, how we organize, how we manifest, how we act collectively, as a state and nation. 
      p In that sense, politics is in every area of ​​our existence. From what we wear to whom we support.
      p For example, feminism, a movement that fights for the liberation of women, is an intrinsically political movement, because it's about revolution of our lives. When we understand it in this way we understand that the musical genres that denigrate and / or minimize our bodies like reggaeton, are part of the problem. We also understand that we cannot talk about recovery of rights for some and not for all, so feminism cannot want to consolidate the current socioeconomic system in which we live because it is a system that generates inequality gaps so high that <a href = "https : //www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-42776299 "target =" _ blank "> 1% of the rich accumulate 82% of global wealth </a>
      p Another recent but increasingly important movement is transparency and access to public information. In times where technology is mimicked in our lives with greater force, we can realize that all the time we are generating and consuming information and that our data becomes a new currency.
      p Therefore, we can use this logic to identify in our society the problems to be solved and their causes if we begin to measure our interaction; This is the information generated in our citizenship. For example, when boarding a bus or visiting a park. 
      p On the other hand, the budgets, the registry of visits, the contracts, the redistribution of works and goods, etc. are public information generated from the state and the public function that serves us citizens to contribute to a free and informed public opinion and in this way control the power.
